Read the following article and answer the following questions.

bars_vs_grocery_stores

  1. List one thing you learned from the article:
Solution

Wisconsin is the âbeer belly of Americaâ because its ratio of bars to grocery stores is much higher than the rest of the country.

  1. How did the main visualization (United States) enhance the article?
Solution

The main visualization demonstrated the magnitude to which bars outnumbered grocery stores and vice versa. Instead of simply indicating which areas had more of one than another, including the magnitude of difference allows us to see clearer patterns for each region.

Visualization 2

Open this dashboard and answer the following questions.

  1. What story is this dashboard telling and how do the visualizations enhance that?
Solution

This dashboard provides a breakdown of flights over a yearâs span for several major airlines. The dashboard provides information on the quantity and destination of flights over a monthly and cumulative basis (one year). The dashboard allows people to compare flight volume, destinations, and reliability for each airline.

The visualizations, whether it be over the course of a month or the entire year, provide a breakdown of flight volume by either day or month. This provides insight on which airlines are busiest during certain time periods. The destination visualizations help provide insights into which airports are more common for certain airlines, which can help people decide which airline to book for certain desinations. For example, if an airline (like Delta) flies into Atlanta quite often, it might be easier to find cheaper flights on Delta if someone is planning on travelling to Atlanta.

  1. What might a dashboard provide that a static graphic cannot.
Solution

While this dashboard doesnât seem to be currently updating, one benefit of a dashboard is that it can reflect real-time data, whereas a static graphic is based on a fixed set of data. Thus, a dashboard can reflect changes and updates. Additionally, dashboards are able to be customized because they allow for users to select which visualizations and statistics to display.

Exercise 2

Letâs look at some interesting patterns in the history of LEGO! Weâll be using data from the lego package located data/legosets.rda.

First, letâs look at the average cost of LEGO sets over time. The main variable of interest here is USD_MSRP, or the manufacturerâs suggested retail price in constant dollars.

Solution 
# data wrangling
lego_avg <- legosets %>%
  group_by(Year) %>% 
  summarise(avg_usd_msrp = mean(USD_MSRP,na.rm = TRUE))

#plot
ggplot(data=lego_avg, 
       mapping=aes(x=Year, y=avg_usd_msrp)
) + geom_point() + geom_line() +
  labs(
    x='Year',
    y = "Price (USD)",
    title = "Average price of LEGO sets",
    subtitle = "Amounts reporting in current USD",
    caption = "Source: LEGO"
  ) + theme_minimal()

Exercise 3

Letâs explore how many unique themes LEGO now offers.

What is bad/ugly about the plot above?

Solution

The plot is not that readable. There are too many themes included in the visualization which prevents us from determining which bars correspond to a certain theme. Additionally, the lack of any ordering prevents any ability to determine which themes have the highest and lowest counts.

Now remake the plot BUT with the improvements addressing the issues you noted above.

Solution 
#l label: improved-barplot

# data wrangling
theme_counts <- legosets %>%
  count(Theme, sort=TRUE) %>%
  mutate(Theme = fct_inorder(Theme)%>%fct_rev())

# plot
theme_counts %>%
  filter(Theme != "Duplo")%>%
  filter(n >= 100) %>%
  #slice_max(order_by = n, n=5)%>%
  ggplot(aes(y = Theme, x = n)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_segment(aes(x=0, y=Theme, xend=n, yend=Theme)) + 
  labs(
    x = "Number of Sets",
    y = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Exercise 4

Now you try, letâs look at how the number of pieces per set has changed over time. Because Duplo sets are much smaller (since theyâre designed for toddlers), we made a special indicator variable for them shown in the code below.

Use an appropriate graph to plot the average number of pieces over time. Have either separate lines or separate plots for the Duplo and Lego categories. Be sure the title, x-axis, and y-axis are properly labeled.

Solution 
# data wrangling
pieces_per_year <- legosets %>%
  # new indicator variable
  mutate(Duplo = ifelse(Theme == "Duplo", "Duplo", "Lego"))%>%
  group_by(Year, Duplo)%>%
  summarize(avg_num_pieces = mean(Pieces, na.rm=TRUE))%>%
  ungroup()

# facet
pieces_per_year%>%
  filter(Year>1985)%>%
  ggplot(
    mapping=aes(x=Year, y=avg_num_pieces)
) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line() +
  labs(
    x='Year',
    y = "Number of Pieces",
    title = "Average number of pieces in a LEGO set over time",
    caption = "Source: LEGO"
  ) + 
  facet_wrap(~Duplo, scales="free_y") +
  theme_minimal()

What trends do you notice in the plots? Are you surprised by the plots?

Even though they are on different scales, the average number of pieces in a set for both categories seems to be generally increasing over time. One interesting note for the âDuploâ graph is that after some variations in mean number of pieces, this number seems to have stabilized at just above 40 for the last few years. What surprises me is that despite the stabilization in the Duplo graph, the mean number of pieces for sets in the âLegoâ category seems to be increasingly greatly since 2010.
